    "# Quick Start\n",
    "\n",
    "This is the basics of using ysoisochrone\n",
    "\n",
    "## Installation\n",
    "\n",
    "### Install the package\n",
    "\n",
    "The easiest way to install this package is using terminal, and change directory to the root direcotry of this package (where the `setup.py` exists).\n",
    "\n",
    "```bash \n",
    "pip install .\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "which should install the necessary dependencies.\n",
    "\n",
    "First make sure you have successfully installed the package. You can find out this by trying to import"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import ysoisochrone"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Download the stellar evolutionary models\n",
    "\n",
    "When using the package for the first time, it will try to download the isochrones from online sources, so make sure you also have internet access. You might need to download some large files ($\\sim 1\\,$GB) for using the isochrones from certain models (such as PARSEC), so you also need to make sure you have a few GB left in the disk where you need to store the data.\n",
    "\n",
    "By default, the code will create a folder called `isochrones_data` in the same directory that you are running the `Python` script. You can also change this by editing the `save_dir` argument in the `download_xxx` functions.\n",
    "\n",
    "First, let's try to download the track from [Baraffe et al. (2015)](https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2015A%26A...577A..42B/abstract) and  [Feiden (2016)](https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2016A%26A...593A..99F/abstract)."
   ]
  },
  {

   "execution_count": null,

    "## Your first target"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Prepare the data\n",
    "\n",
    "Then, you need to prepare your own data. The data needs to be in the format of `pandas.DataFrame` and with following columns `['Source', 'Teff[K]', 'e_Teff[K]', 'Luminosity[Lsun]', 'e_Luminosity[Lsun]']`. \n",
    "\n",
    "- `'Source'` is the list of source names. It can be just the ID numbers you prefer.\n",
    "- `'Teff[K]'` is the effective temperature in the unit of Kelvin.\n",
    "- and `'e_Teff[K]'` is the associated uncertainties. \n",
    "- `'Luminosity[Lsun]'` is the bolometric luminosities of these targets un the unit of solar luminosity. \n",
    "- and `'e_Luminosity[Lsun]'` is their uncertainties.\n",
    "\n",
    "Here the uncertainties are $1\\,\\sigma$ value assuming they follow the Gaussian distribution."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Set up a DataFrame in Python script\n",
    "\n",
    "df_prop = pd.DataFrame({\n",
    "    'Source': ['Sz65'],\n",
    "    'Teff[K]': np.array([4060.0]),\n",
    "    'e_Teff[K]': np.array([187.0]),\n",
    "    'Luminosity[Lsun]': np.array([0.869]),\n",
    "    'e_Luminosity[Lsun]': np.array([0.3623])\n",
    "})"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Plot it on the HRD"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 3600x1800 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "\n",
    "ylim_set = [1e-2, 10]\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(12, 6),gridspec_kw={'wspace':0.1})\n",
    "\n",
    "# set up the Isochrone class\n",
    "isochrone = ysoisochrone.isochrone.Isochrone()\n",
    "isochrone.set_tracks('Feiden2016')\n",
    "\n",
    "ysoisochrone.plotting.plot_hr_diagram(isochrone, df_prop, ax_set=axes[0], xlim_set=[5000, 3900], ylim_set=ylim_set)\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[0].get_legend().remove()\n",
    "axes[0].annotate('Feiden 2016', xy=(0.95, 0.95), xycoords='axes fraction', ha='right', va='top', fontsize=20)\n",
    "\n",
    "# set up the Isochrone class\n",
    "isochrone = ysoisochrone.isochrone.Isochrone()\n",
    "isochrone.set_tracks('Baraffe2015')\n",
    "\n",
    "ysoisochrone.plotting.plot_hr_diagram(isochrone, df_prop, ax_set=axes[1], xlim_set=[3900, 3000], ylim_set=ylim_set)\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[1].set_ylabel('')\n",
    "axes[1].annotate('Baraffe+2015', xy=(0.95, 0.95), xycoords='axes fraction', ha='right', va='top', fontsize=20)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Here the blue points with errorbars are the stars with uncertainties; dark red solid lines are the stellar evolutionary tracks for different stellar masses; dashed grey lines are the isochorones; We also have an algrithm to automatically detect the zero-age-main-sequence (ZAMS) curve in the tracks, and that is shown as magenta dot-dashed line. \n",
    "\n",
    "**NOTE** \n",
    "\n",
    "- *On each track, the points that are older than the ZAMS will be ignored in the age/mass determination later.*\n",
    "- *For the targets that are very close to ZAMS, their estimated ages cannot be trusted blindly, and they are in general less reliable*"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Estimate its age and mass from Bayesian inference approach\n",
    "\n",
    "Our primary method is a Bayesian inference approach, and the `Python` code builds on the `IDL` version developed in [Pascucci et al. (2016)](https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2016ApJ...831..125P/abstract). \n",
    "The pre-main-sequence evolutionary models from both [Feiden (2016)](https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2016A%26A...593A..99F/abstract) and [Baraffe et al. (2015)](https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2015A%26A...577A..42B/abstract) are adopted for hot ($T_{\\rm eff} > 3,900$) and cool stars ($T_{\\rm eff} \\leq 3,900$), respectively.\n",
    "\n",
    "We provide a simple way to use this as"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "  0%|          | 0/1 [00:00<?, ?it/s]/Users/dingshandeng/github/ysoisochrone/ysoisochrone/plotting.py:129: MatplotlibDeprecationWarning: Starting from Matplotlib 3.6, colorbar() will steal space from the mappable's axes, rather than from the current axes, to place the colorbar.  To silence this warning, explicitly pass the 'ax' argument to colorbar().\n",
      "  cb = plt.colorbar(im)\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1800x1500 with 4 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    },
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "100%|██████████| 1/1 [00:00<00:00,  2.50it/s]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "best_logmass_output, best_logage_output, lmass_all, lage_all =\\\n",
    "    ysoisochrone.bayesian.derive_stellar_mass_age(df_prop, model='Baraffe_n_Feiden', plot=True)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The `model` here is for calling different evolutionary tracks, by default we use `model='Baraffe_n_Feiden'`, which is the combination of Baraffe and Feiden tracks. Other choices include: `'Baraffe2015'`, `'Feiden2016'`, `'PARSEC_v2p0'` (same as `'PARSEC'`), `'PARSEC_v1p2'` or `'custome'`. If you want to use your own customized isochrone, you need to set the `model = 'custome'`, and also provide the absolute directory for the isochrone matrix file `isochrone_mat_file`. See [documentation](https://ysoisochrone.readthedocs.io/en/latest/index.html) for details. Here we also turn on the `plot = True` to show the intermediate diagnoostic plot."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The outputs are:\n",
    "(a) `best_logmass_output` (log10 of mass in the unit of solar masses), `best_logage_output` (log10 of age in the unit of yrs) are the arrays that includes the best derived values and their lower and upper boundaries from the 68% confidence intervals. \n",
    "(b) `lmass_all` and `lage_all` are the distributions of the likelihood functions for each source; they could be used to estimate the medians based on the likelihood distributions.\n",
    "\n",
    "An example of saving these outputs are"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "For target Sz65\n",
      "The estimated mass is: 0.68 + 0.20 - 0.14 [Msun]\n",
      "The estimated age is: 1.17 + 1.06 - 0.60 [Myrs]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "df_output_mass = pd.DataFrame(np.array(best_logmass_output), columns=['logmass[Msun]', 'lw_logmass[Msun]', 'up_logmass[Msun]'])\n",
    "df_output_age = pd.DataFrame(np.array(best_logage_output), columns=['logage[yrs]', 'lw_logage[yrs]', 'up_logage[yrs]']) \n",
    "df_output = pd.concat([df_prop, df_output_mass, df_output_age], axis=1)\n",
    "\n",
    "df_output.loc[:, 'mass[Msun]'] = 10**df_output.loc[:, 'logmass[Msun]']\n",
    "df_output.loc[:, 'lw_mass[Msun]'] = 10**df_output.loc[:, 'lw_logmass[Msun]']\n",
    "df_output.loc[:, 'up_mass[Msun]'] = 10**df_output.loc[:, 'up_logmass[Msun]']\n",
    "\n",
    "df_output.loc[:, 'age[Myrs]'] = 10**df_output.loc[:, 'logage[yrs]']/1e6\n",
    "df_output.loc[:, 'lw_age[Myrs]'] = 10**df_output.loc[:, 'lw_logage[yrs]']/1e6\n",
    "df_output.loc[:, 'up_age[Myrs]'] = 10**df_output.loc[:, 'up_logage[yrs]']/1e6\n",
    "\n",
    "for idx in df_output.index:\n",
    "    print('For target %s'%(df_output.loc[idx, 'Source']))\n",
    "    print('The estimated mass is: %.2f + %.2f - %.2f [Msun]'%(df_output.loc[idx, 'mass[Msun]'],\\\n",
    "            df_output.loc[idx, 'up_mass[Msun]']-df_output.loc[idx, 'mass[Msun]'],\\\n",
    "            df_output.loc[idx, 'mass[Msun]']-df_output.loc[idx, 'lw_mass[Msun]']))\n",
    "    print('The estimated age is: %.2f + %.2f - %.2f [Myrs]'%(df_output.loc[idx, 'age[Myrs]'],\\\n",
    "            df_output.loc[idx, 'up_age[Myrs]']-df_output.loc[idx, 'age[Myrs]'],\\\n",
    "            df_output.loc[idx, 'age[Myrs]']-df_output.loc[idx, 'lw_age[Myrs]']))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The distribution of the two likelihood functions for mass and age (`lmass` and `lage`) for this target has already been presented in the plot above. But if you want to take a look again, you can read them out follow this plotting script"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1800x600 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "idx = 0\n",
    "lmass_t = lmass_all['target_%i'%(idx)]\n",
    "lage_t = lage_all['target_%i'%(idx)]\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(6, 2),gridspec_kw={'wspace':0.15})\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[0].plot(lmass_t[0], lmass_t[1], color='k')\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[0].axvline(df_output.loc[idx, 'logmass[Msun]'])\n",
    "axes[0].axvline(df_output.loc[idx, 'up_logmass[Msun]'], linestyle='--')\n",
    "axes[0].axvline(df_output.loc[idx, 'lw_logmass[Msun]'], linestyle='--')\n",
    "\n",
    "text_mass = 'estimated mass\\n' + '${%.2f}^{+%.2f}_{-%.2f}\\,[M_\\odot]$'%(df_output.loc[idx, 'mass[Msun]'],\\\n",
    "            df_output.loc[idx, 'up_mass[Msun]']-df_output.loc[idx, 'mass[Msun]'],\\\n",
    "            df_output.loc[idx, 'mass[Msun]']-df_output.loc[idx, 'lw_mass[Msun]'])\n",
    "axes[0].annotate(text_mass, xy=(0.95, 0.95), xycoords='axes fraction', ha='right', va='top', fontsize=8)\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[0].set_xlabel(r'$\\log_{10}\\,{\\rm Mass}\\,[M_\\odot]$')\n",
    "axes[0].set_ylabel('Likelihood')\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[1].plot(lage_t[0], lage_t[1], color='k')\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[1].axvline(df_output.loc[idx, 'logage[yrs]'])\n",
    "axes[1].axvline(df_output.loc[idx, 'up_logage[yrs]'], linestyle='--')\n",
    "axes[1].axvline(df_output.loc[idx, 'lw_logage[yrs]'], linestyle='--')\n",
    "\n",
    "text_age = 'estimated age\\n' + '${%.2f}^{+%.2f}_{-%.2f}\\,$[Myrs]'%(df_output.loc[idx, 'age[Myrs]'],\\\n",
    "            df_output.loc[idx, 'up_age[Myrs]']-df_output.loc[idx, 'age[Myrs]'],\\\n",
    "            df_output.loc[idx, 'age[Myrs]']-df_output.loc[idx, 'lw_age[Myrs]'])\n",
    "axes[1].annotate(text_age, xy=(0.95, 0.95), xycoords='axes fraction', ha='right', va='top', fontsize=8)\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[1].set_xlabel(r'$\\log_{10}\\,{\\rm Age}\\,[{\\rm yrs}]$')\n",
    "axes[1].set_ylabel('')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",

    "# Then you can save this output file\n",
    "df_output.to_csv('example_target_one_o.csv', index=False)"
   ]

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Your first large dataset"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Read in a csv table\n",
    "\n",
    "When dealing with larger dataset, the easiest way is to create a `.csv` file using EXCEL or similar software, and this file includes these columns, and then you can utilize `pandas` to read in this file. Later you use this as an input.\n",
    "\n",
    "Here we prepared an example file called `'example_targets.csv'` in this tutorial. This is part of the Cham I sample that discussed in [Pascucci et al. (2016)](https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2016ApJ...831..125P/abstract)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/html": [
       "<div>\n",

       "    .dataframe tbody tr th {\n",
       "        vertical-align: top;\n",
       "    }\n",
       "\n",
       "    .dataframe thead th {\n",
       "        text-align: right;\n",
       "    }\n",

       "      <td>1.210</td>\n",
       "      <td>0.8633</td>\n",
       "    </tr>\n",
       "  </tbody>\n",
       "</table>\n",
       "</div>"
      ],
      "text/plain": [
       "              Source  Teff[K]  e_Teff[K]  Luminosity[Lsun]  e_Luminosity[Lsun]\n",
       "0               Sz65     4060      187.0             0.869              0.3623\n",
       "1               Sz71     3632      167.0             0.327              0.1420\n",
       "2  J16124373-3815031     3705      171.0             0.390              0.2691\n",
       "3               Sz72     3560      164.0             0.272              0.1160\n",
       "4               Sz77     4060      187.0             0.593              0.2428\n",
       "5  J16085324-3914401     3415       79.0             0.198              0.1477\n",
       "6              Sz131     3415       79.0             0.150              0.0583\n",
       "7               Sz66     3415       79.0             0.216              0.0920\n",
       "8               Sz95     3415       79.0             0.267              0.1842\n",
       "9           V1094Sco     4205      193.0             1.210              0.8633"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "df_prop = pd.read_csv('example_targets.csv')\n",
    "\n",
    "df_prop"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**NOTE**\n",
    "\n",
    "The uncertainties for $T_{\\rm eff}$ and $L$ are required in this approach, if you have no idea on what would be the `'e_Teff[K]'` and/or `'e_Luminosity[Lsun]'` (or just want a quick test), you can turn on the option `no_uncertainties=True` in `ysoisochrone.bayesian.derive_stellar_mass_age`. In this way, the code will automatically assign the uncertainties to your sample following the choice made in [Pascucci et al. (2016)](https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2016ApJ...831..125P/abstract) with the pre-assumed uncertainties for $T_{\\rm eff}$ and $L$: \n",
    "\n",
    "- $\\sigma(\\log_{10}{T_{\\rm eff}}) = 0.02$ for $T_{\\rm eff} > 3420.0\\,{\\rm K}$ and $\\sigma(\\log_{10}{T_{\\rm eff}}) = 0.01$ for cooler targets.\n",
    "- $\\sigma(\\log_{10}L = 0.1)$ for all targets\n",
    "\n",
    "You can also assign these default uncertainties to your `DataFrame` (`df_prop`) by calling\n",
    "\n",
    "```python\n",
    "err_Teff = ysoisochrone.utils.assign_unc_teff(df_prop['Teff[K]'].values)\n",
    "err_Lumi = ysoisochrone.utils.assign_unc_lumi(df_prop['Luminosity[Lsun]'].values)\n",
    "df_prop['e_Teff[K]'] = err_Teff\n",
    "df_prop['e_Luminosity[Lsun]'] = err_Lumi\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "*we encourage the users to set up your own uncertainties* in the input `df_prop` for your targets even you do not have the meausred values. You can do this by changing the numbers in the input `.csv` file or utilize the feature for `pandas.DataFrame` \n",
    "\n",
    "```python\n",
    "df_prop.loc[:, 'e_Teff[K]'] = # An array of the e_Teff you set up\n",
    "df_prop.loc[:, 'e_Luminosity[Lsun]'] = # An array of the e_Luminosity you set up\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**TIPS** \n",
    "\n",
    "`pandas.DataFrame` is a very versatile class. Please refer to [Data Frame](https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/reference/api/pandas.DataFrame.html) for how to handle the `pandas.DataFrame`. It is a powerful tool that you can not only import data from `.csv` files but many other format such as `.xlsx`, `.json`, and `.html`. For theo output files, it can also be utilized to generate `latex` format files `.tex` so it can be easily import to your on going `latex` manuscript."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Have a look on HRD\n",
    "\n",
    "You can overplot them on the top of the isochrones in the Hertzsprung–Russell diagram (HR diagram)."

    "\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(12, 6),gridspec_kw={'wspace':0.1})\n",
    "\n",
    "# set up the Isochrone class\n",
    "isochrone = ysoisochrone.isochrone.Isochrone()\n",
    "isochrone.set_tracks('Feiden2016')\n",
    "\n",
    "ysoisochrone.plotting.plot_hr_diagram(isochrone, df_prop, ax_set=axes[0], xlim_set=[5000, 3900], ylim_set=ylim_set)\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[0].get_legend().remove()\n",
    "axes[0].annotate('Feiden 2016', xy=(0.95, 0.95), xycoords='axes fraction', ha='right', va='top', fontsize=20)\n",
    "\n",
    "# set up the Isochrone class\n",

    "isochrone.set_tracks('Baraffe2015')\n",
    "\n",
    "ysoisochrone.plotting.plot_hr_diagram(isochrone, df_prop, ax_set=axes[1], xlim_set=[3900, 3000], ylim_set=ylim_set)\n",

    "axes[1].annotate('Baraffe+2015', xy=(0.95, 0.95), xycoords='axes fraction', ha='right', va='top', fontsize=20)\n",

   "source": [
    "df_output_mass = pd.DataFrame(np.array(best_logmass_output), columns=['logmass[Msun]', 'lw_logmass[Msun]', 'up_logmass[Msun]'])\n",
    "df_output_age = pd.DataFrame(np.array(best_logage_output), columns=['logage[yrs]', 'lw_logage[yrs]', 'up_logage[yrs]']) \n",
    "df_output = pd.concat([df_prop, df_output_mass, df_output_age], axis=1)\n",
    "\n",
    "df_output.loc[:, 'mass[Msun]'] = 10**df_output.loc[:, 'logmass[Msun]']\n",
    "df_output.loc[:, 'lw_mass[Msun]'] = 10**df_output.loc[:, 'lw_logmass[Msun]']\n",
    "df_output.loc[:, 'up_mass[Msun]'] = 10**df_output.loc[:, 'up_logmass[Msun]']\n",
    "\n",
    "df_output.loc[:, 'age[Myrs]'] = 10**df_output.loc[:, 'logage[yrs]']/1e6\n",
    "df_output.loc[:, 'lw_age[Myrs]'] = 10**df_output.loc[:, 'lw_logage[yrs]']/1e6\n",
    "df_output.loc[:, 'up_age[Myrs]'] = 10**df_output.loc[:, 'up_logage[yrs]']/1e6\n",
    "\n",
    "df_output"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Then you can save this output file\n",
    "df_output.to_csv('example_targets_o.csv', index=False)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Quick demo on other methods\n",
    "\n",
    "Now you already know how to work with your dataset, here we provide a quick demo on how to utilize other methods provided in this package"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Closest grid point on isochrone\n",
    "\n",
    "Of course we provide this option for you to simply estimate the stellar masses and ages from the grid point that has the closest $T_{\\rm eff}$ and $L_{\\rm bol}$ to the target without using any Bayesian inference. This was the approach adopted in many literature works."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "100%|██████████| 1/1 [00:00<00:00, 12.82it/s]"
     ]
    },
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Working on: Sz65\n",
      "Closest match for Sz65: Age = 1.32e+06 yrs, Mass = 6.52e-01 Msun\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "df_prop_t = df_prop.loc[:0]\n",
    "\n",
    "best_logmass_output, best_logage_output = ysoisochrone.bayesian.derive_stellar_mass_age_closest_track(df_prop_t, model='Baraffe_n_Feiden', verbose=True)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**NOTE** In this method, we do not estimate the uncertainties. The output best-fit logmass and logage are the closest track and no uncertainties are provided."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Assuming age to derive stellar masses\n",
    "\n",
    "In some cases, when a good measurement of stellar luminosity is unavailable,  we also provide an option to set up the assumed age (`assumed_age=1.5e6` in the example, it is in the unit of yr) to derive the stellar mass from the Bayesian inference. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 2400x1800 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    },
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "The estimated mass is: 0.65 + 0.13 - 0.11 [Msun]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# only take one target as an example\n",
    "idx = 0\n",
    "df_prop_t = df_prop.loc[[idx]]\n",
    "\n",
    "best_logmass_output_t = ysoisochrone.bayesian.derive_stellar_mass_assuming_age(df_prop_t, assumed_age=1.5e6, model='Baraffe_n_Feiden', plot=True)\n",
    "\n",
    "df_output_mass_t = pd.DataFrame(np.array(best_logmass_output_t), columns=['logmass[Msun]', 'lw_logmass[Msun]', 'up_logmass[Msun]'])\n",
    "df_output_t = pd.concat([df_prop_t, df_output_mass_t], axis=1)\n",
    "df_output_t.loc[:, 'mass[Msun]'] = 10**df_output_t.loc[:, 'logmass[Msun]']\n",
    "df_output_t.loc[:, 'lw_mass[Msun]'] = 10**df_output_t.loc[:, 'lw_logmass[Msun]']\n",
    "df_output_t.loc[:, 'up_mass[Msun]'] = 10**df_output_t.loc[:, 'up_logmass[Msun]']\n",
    "\n",
    "print('The estimated mass is: %.2f + %.2f - %.2f [Msun]'%(df_output_t.loc[idx, 'mass[Msun]'],\\\n",
    "                      df_output_t.loc[idx, 'up_mass[Msun]']-df_output_t.loc[idx, 'mass[Msun]'],\\\n",
    "                      df_output_t.loc[idx, 'mass[Msun]']-df_output_t.loc[idx, 'lw_mass[Msun]']))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Or you can simply get the one with closest track, and this is the method adopted in [Pascucci et al. (2016)](https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2016ApJ...831..125P/abstract) for the targets that do not have good luminosity measurement. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "estimated mass: 0.65 [Msun]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# only take one target as an example\n",
    "idx = 0\n",
    "df_prop_t = df_prop.loc[[idx]]\n",
    "\n",
    "best_logmass_output_t = ysoisochrone.bayesian.derive_stellar_mass_assuming_age_closest_trk(df_prop_t, assumed_age=1.5e6, model='Baraffe_n_Feiden')\n",
    "\n",
    "print('estimated mass: %.2f [Msun]'%(10**best_logmass_output_t))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**NOTE** In this way, the uncertainties will not be provided, and only the best fit mass is the out put."
   ]
